From: MINORI IKEDA <daisysi9@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] util: fix NULL dereference in ptyxis_path_expand()

When wordexp() fails (e.g. out of memory, or bad input), `ret` remains
NULL. The subsequent call to g_path_is_absolute(ret) then dereferences
NULL, causing a crash.

Also add a fallback: if ret is still NULL after all expansion attempts,
return a copy of the original path rather than NULL, matching the
documented return type ("A newly allocated string").

This crash was observed on OpenBSD (where wordexp(3) is not available
and wordexp() always returns an error code), but the NULL dereference
can occur on any platform when wordexp() fails.
---
 src/ptyxis-util.c | 5 +++--
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

--- a/src/ptyxis-util.c
+++ b/src/ptyxis-util.c
@@ -208,12 +208,13 @@ ptyxis_path_expand (const char *path)
   if (r == 0 && state.we_wordc > 0)
     ret = g_strdup (state.we_wordv [0]);
   wordfree (&state);

-  if (!g_path_is_absolute (ret))
+  if (ret != NULL && !g_path_is_absolute (ret))
     {
       g_autofree char *freeme = ret;

       ret = g_build_filename (g_get_home_dir (), freeme, NULL);
     }

   g_free (replace_home);
   g_free (escaped);

-  return ret;
+  return ret != NULL ? ret : g_strdup (path);
 }
